topic.name: Identities & Equations
topic.description: 13-year academic progression (K-12) for Identities & Equations in Mathematics

objectives.objective_text: Name cutting a number in half.
Identify a puzzle piece that fits.
Name synonyms (words that mean the same).
Identify the goal: isolate the trig function.
Identify that two pictures are the same.
Recall that we can break numbers apart.
Recall that $1+2$ is the same as $3$.
Recall that we want to know 'what fits'.
Explain how to find values for double angles.
Check if two sides are equal.
Defend the derivation of the Pythagorean identities.
Explain that there might be more than one answer.
Explain how to use the formulas.
Defend the logic of the expansion.
Summarize proving that Left Side = Right Side.
Explain that we can't move things across the equals sign.
Simplify one side to match the other.
Defend the validity of the identity.
Analyze the derivation from Sum identities.
Interpret the choice of three formulas for $cos(2A)$.
Interpret this as the Pythagorean theorem on the unit circle.
Analyze equations with multiple functions (use identities).
Connect factoring to solving quadratics in sine.
Connect exact values to sum/difference formulas.
Analyze strategies (change to sine/cosine, common denominator).
Evaluate integration strategies using power reduction.
Evaluate the domain validity of identities.
Evaluate solutions within a specific interval.
Evaluate the proof of the sum formulas.
Evaluate the most efficient path to proof.
Construct proofs using double angle identities.
Construct exact values for non-standard angles (e.g., 15 degrees).
Construct rigorous proofs for complex identities.
Synthesize algebraic skills with trig definitions.
Defend the utility of these identities in calculus.
